Action Name: Host CLI - Add Program to Windows Startup Script, All Users
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the addition of an executable to the Windows startup folder. Programs or scripts added to "C:\ProgramData\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup" will automatically execute whenever any user logs into Windows. Malicious actors take advantage of this behavior as a persistence mechanism on targeted hosts. This behavior can also be leveraged for lateral movement if pushed to other systems via Group Policy.

The program added to startup is a legitimate copy of calc.exe and is removed by Action cleanup.
Tags: ATT&CK:Persistence, CWE:284, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:T1037, CAPEC:564

Action Name: Host CLI - Add Program to Windows Startup Script, Current User
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the addition of an executable to the Windows startup folder for the currently logged in user. Programs or scripts added to "C:\Users\%USERNAME%\AppData\Roaming\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup" will automatically execute whenever the user logs in. Malicious actors take advantage of this behavior as a persistence mechanism on targeted accounts. This behavior can also be leveraged for lateral movement as the script will run on any computer the user logs into in the future.

The program added to startup is a legitimate copy of calc.exe and is removed by Action cleanup.
Tags: ATT&CK:Persistence, CWE:284, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:T1037, CAPEC:564

Action Name: Host CLI - RYUK, FIN12, Active Directory Reconnaissance
Action Description:
This action demonstrates the use of several commands for reconnaissance.  These commands were observed being run by FIN12, after a breaching a network.  These commands return Active Directory users and admins, network configuration data, and trusted domains.

RYUK is a ransomware that uses a combination of public and symmetric-key cryptography to encrypt files on the host computer. The malware stops numerous services and kills a variety of processes that may interfere with its ransomware functionality, most of which are related to anti-virus, database, and back-up software. It will recurse through all drives on the system and use the WNet functions on accessible network resources to encrypt files. More information about RYUK can be found on the [Mandiant Advantage Summary Page](https://advantage.mandiant.com/malware/malware--c504771c-24eb-53b5-8d7e-42d59bf5c0fd). More information about FIN12 can be found on the [Mandiant Advantage Summary Page](https://advantage.mandiant.com/actors/threat-actor--14e31117-b933-5349-9d9b-0a3b395380e9).

>**Pre-Requisites:**
Actor must be domain-joined to properly configured Active Directory environment
Tags: CAPEC:577, ATT&CK:T1482, ATT&CK:T1033, Malware:RYUK, FIN12, CAPEC:575, ATT&CK:T1087, CWE:200, ATT&CK:Discovery, Ransomware, Active Directory

Action Name: Host CLI - Registry Key Modifications
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates an Actor attempting to modify a registry entry to create a persistence method for a downloaded malicious executable. Registry modification is a common technique used by actors and malicious files for persistence, as the activity may easily blend in with regular system activity.

Please note, the binary included in this Action connects to a loopback address (127.0.0.1).

Action Name: Host CLI - Scheduled Task Called by Run Key, Highest Privileges
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the setup of scheduled tasks called by a run key for persistence.  This technique was observed in use by FIN12, prior to deployment of the RYUK ransomware.  In this case, the scheduled tasks are set to use highest privileges.  FIN12, was observed attempting to create these tasks both with and without highest privileges, as creation with highest privileges could fail.

For more information, click [here](https://thedfirreport.com/2020/11/05/ryuk-speed-run-2-hours-to-ransom/)

Action Name: Host CLI - Bypass UAC
Action Description: This Action demonstrates an Actor attempting to disable UAC on an endpoint. UAC, or User Account Control, is a Windows security component that enforces the concept of least privilege. UAC will execute applications and processes with Non-administrative privilege regardless of permissions associated with the executing account.  The registry change included in this Action will disable UAC so that applications and processes will be run with Administrative privilege so long as the account has appropriate permission.
Tags: ATT&CK:T1088, ATT&CK:T1548.002, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, CWE:284

Action Name: Host CLI - Timestomp W/ PowerShell
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a PowerShell timestomp to modify metadata and make detection of malicious activity more difficult. Timestomping is an anti-forensics technique used by adversaries in order to make suspicious files blend in with other files in a directory or look as though certain files were never accessed. It is also used in an attempt to alter the timeline of events following a compromise. This technique includes changing the different timestamps of a file including time created, last accessed, last modified, and change times.

This Action will create a new file and then change the timestamps of the file to a different time. The file will be removed with the Action cleanup.
Tags: ATT&CK:T1099, ATT&CK:T1070.006, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion

Action Name: Host CLI - Creation of a Volume Shadow Copy
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates how a user can use PowerShell to create a new volume shadow copy. These copies can be automatically scheduled to backup, or a user can also manually create a new copy. Volume shadow copies contain backups of files and the data stored on a defined drive of the computer during the time the copy was created. These volume shadow copies can contain sensitive content that adversaries could target for exfiltration.

After the creation of the new copy, the Action cleanup will delete it.

Action Name: Host CLI - PowerShell Without PowerShell
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the bypassing of PowerShell restrictions and/or monitoring.  The vast majority of users do not need to use PowerShell, while attackers continuously demonstrate their ability to leverage PowerShell's capabilities to compromise networks.  As a result, defenders will sometimes restrict the use of PowerShell to users with a legitimate business use.  However, these restrictions can be bypassed with clever tricks.  This Action uses csc.exe, a native C# compiler to compile a program that can execute PowerShell scripts.

More about this technique can be found [here.](https://www.blackhillsinfosec.com/powershell-w-o-powershell-simplified/)

Action Name: Host CLI - MSBuildShell
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the use of msbuild.exe to create a PowerShell-like shell by calling the .NET framework.  This shell is one way that attackers can attempt to bypass application whitelisting. Also, by using msbuild to compile the shell allows attackers to access PowerShell functionality when access to PowerShell is denied by policy.  

More information on this technique can be found [here](https://web.archive.org/web/20161212224652/http://subt0x10.blogspot.com/2016/09/bypassing-application-whitelisting.html) and [here.](https://github.com/Cn33liz/MSBuildShell)

Action Name: Host CLI - Logon Script
Action Description: This Action demonstrates how a script can be registered to run when a specific user logs onto a device. Windows allows for the ability to run scripts at login for specific or groups of users. Creation of logon scripts will add new registry keys to HKCU\Environment. While logon scripts are often used for Administrative purposes, adversaries can take advantage of these feature for persistence and lateral movement on a compromised machine.
Tags: ATT&CK:Persistence, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:T1112, CWE:732, CWE:284, CWE:15, CAPEC:203, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:T1037, CAPEC:564

Action Name: Host CLI - Image File Execution Options (Debugger)
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates how a debugger is assigned to an application using Image File Execution Options (IFEO). In this Action, a new registry key is added under HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Image File Execution Options so when Internet Explorer is launched, notepad.exe runs as its debugger. This can be seen in the screenshot provided following the completion of a job (Note: No screenshots will be available if the job ran as System).

Adversaries can leverage IFEO by assigning malicious applications as the debugger for commonly used programs to gain persistence and privilege escalation on a compromised machine.
Tags: ATT&CK:T1183, ATT&CK:T1546.012, ATT&CK:T1112, CWE:732, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, CWE:15, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, CAPEC:203, ATT&CK:Persistence

Action Name: Host CLI - New Service
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the compiling of code in C# using native Windows processes, and then the creation of a service using the resulting executable.  Compiling code on the victims machine is one way that attackers can upload malicious files.  

By creating a new service, an attacker attempts to establish a form of persistence.  Additionally, services created by a user with Administrator privileges are executed using System privileges, so this technique can also be considered a method of privilege escalation.

Action Name: Host CLI - Modifying an Existing Service
Action Description:
In this Action, a malicious actor modifies the registry keys to start the Volume Shadow Copy Service on login. Modifying services is a stealthier way for an attacker to establish persistence without creating a new service altogether (A104-164). The volume shadow copy service, in particular, can be valuable for an attacker because it allows attackers to access files that are normally locked such as NTDT.DIT on a domain controller, or the SAM and System files on a workstation.

Services can be changed by either modifying the registry keys or using sc.exe. In this Action, the registry keys are modified.
Tags: ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, CWE:284, ATT&CK:Persistence, CWE:732, CWE:522, ATT&CK:T1031, ATT&CK:T1058, CAPEC:551, CAPEC:478, ATT&CK:T1543.003, ATT&CK:T1574.011, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion

Action Name: Host CLI - Network Sniffing W/ Netsh Trace
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates how netsh trace provides the ability to complete packet captures on a network. Netsh trace is a Windows built-in command line tool that is generally used for completing network traces for troubleshooting purposes. Along with completing trace routes, netsh trace can also capture network packets when capturing is selected at runtime (capture=yes).

Netsh trace is used in this network sniffing example due to the restrictions and limitations of downloading and installing other packet sniffing tools on a device, such as WinDump.

Action Name: Host CLI - Path Interception (Unquoted Paths)
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates how file paths that contain spaces are susceptible to path interceptions. Path interceptions take place when a different executable is run by an application that what was initially intended. There are various methods to path interception that an adversary can use to complete this, including, search order hijacking, misconfiguration of path variables, and unquoted file paths.

In this Action, a new service is created and points to an unquoted file path that includes spaces in the path (C:\Program Files\Common Files\Run.exe). When the service is created and started, the service instead executes a different executable in the higher level directory (C:\Program Files\Common.exe) because of the unquoted file path. Adversaries can take advantage of unquoted file paths to gain persistence on an infected computer. To remediate this type of activity, it is crucial to ensure all file paths are properly quoted ("\"C:\Program Files\Common Files\Run.exe"\").
Tags: CWE:706, CWE:427, CAPEC:159, CWE:428, ATT&CK:T1569.002, ATT&CK:T1035, CWE:426, ATT&CK:T1034, ATT&CK:Persistence, ATT&CK:Execution, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation

Action Name: Host CLI - PowerShell Set Execution Policy
Action Description: This Action attempts to escalate a user's PowerShell execution policy to Unrestricted. The execution policy is used to define what PowerShell scripts can load and run on a device for a specific user or a PowerShell session. Setting the execution policy to unrestricted allows for unsigned scripts to execute. Note: While this increases the chances of running a malicious script, a prompt will appear notifying if the script was originally downloaded from the Internet.

Action Name: Host CLI - PowerShdll Executable
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a malicious attacker using DLLs to create an instance of PowerShell. The PowerShdll executable can be used to create an interactive console as demonstrated in this Action, but it can also be used to run scripts by passing the -f argument and the path of the PowerShell script to be run.

Credit for this work goes to [p3nt4](https://github.com/p3nt4/PowerShdll).

This Action requires .NET v2.0.

Action Name: Host CLI - Squiblydoo
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a malicious attacker using the Regsvr32 program and scrobj.dll to execute an XML file masquerading as an SCT file.  In this case, regsvr32 writes to a new text file under the C:\Users\Public\Documents directory.  However, this technique can be used to download and execute a remote payload as well, all under the guise of a legitimately signed Microsoft binary.

More information on this technique can be found [here](https://www.carbonblack.com/2016/04/28/threat-advisory-squiblydoo-continues-trend-of-attackers-using-native-os-tools-to-live-off-the-land/).

Action Name: Host CLI - InstallUtil Code Execution
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a malicious actor using native .NET framework tools to compile and execute a malicious payload.  The payload, in this case, is C# code that will create a new text file under the C:\Users\Public\Documents directory.  By using legitimately signed Microsoft binaries, this Action demonstrates an attempt to bypass application whitelisting to execute attacker-controlled code.

Credit for this technique goes to Casey Smith.  More information on this technique can be found [here](https://www.blackhillsinfosec.com/how-to-bypass-application-whitelisting-av/).

Action Name: Host CLI - RegAsm Bypass
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates how an attacker can use the RegAsm utility to execute a malicious payload.  RegAsm and RegSvcs are used to register .NET Component Object Model assemblies and are trusted Microsoft binaries.  This Action also uses a C# compiler that is packaged with the .NET framework. In this Action, the payload simply creates a new instance of notepad.

The Strong Name Key (key.snk) included in this Action was created using the [sn.exe utility](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/tools/sn-exe-strong-name-tool).

Credit for this technique goes to Casey Smith.  The C# code for this Action was adapted from the work of [Arn0x](https://gist.github.com/Arno0x).

Action Name: Host CLI - InjectDLL with Application Shimming
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates how a malicious actor can use application shimming to establish a persistence mechanism and execute arbitrary code.  Application shims are normally used to allow for backwards compatibility of products across different versions of Operating Systems.  Compatibility is achieved by intercepting application API calls and altering the way executables are processed.  Application shims are applied using the sdbinst utility.

In this Action, a customized database file is deployed for an executable named A104-221.exe.  Once the application shim is deployed, execution of A104-221.exe will also execute a DLL with arbitrary code.  In this case, the executed code merely creates an empty text file.

FIN7 has been observed using this technique to [establish persistence](https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2017/05/fin7-shim-databases-persistence.html).
Tags: ATT&CK:Persistence, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:T1138, ATT&CK:T1546.011

Action Name: Host CLI - Persistence with Universal Windows Platform Apps Debugger
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a recently identified persistence mechanism that leverages Universal Windows Platform Apps (Appx). This technique was recently released on September 6th, 2018 by [Oddvar Moe](https://oddvar.moe/2018/09/06/persistence-using-universal-windows-platform-apps-appx/).

Universal Windows Platform Apps use a built-in tool called PLMDebug.exe for debugging which includes a command line option that can pass arguments to assist in the debugging. Using this tool with the command line argument option, an adversary can add a registry key for Universal Windows Platform Apps to run in debug mode when a device boots up.

This example, which is explained in more detail in Oddvar Mod's blog, modifies a registry key which opens Cortana in debugging mode after a computer is rebooted. The registry key that is added simply identifies cmd.exe as the debugger, but an adversary can point to a malicious binary to keep its persistence.
Tags: ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:T1112, CWE:732, CWE:15, CAPEC:203

Action Name: Host CLI - Replication Through Removable Media
Action Description:
This Action utilizes the Register-WmiEvent cmdlet to subscribe to Windows Management Instrumentation events. This particular subscription is looking for any events of a USB drive being inserted into the device. The $q variable contains the query that is used to look for this specific events.  It is possible to automatically issue a command using the -Action switch when the query returns related events. Adversaries will use the replication through removable media technique as a means for both initial access onto a system as well as lateral movement, especially in an air-gapped network.

In this example, when a USB is inserted into the device, the usb_alert.ps1 script is executed. The script simply echoes that a USB was inserted into the computer, but this could easily be expanded to copying malicious files to the USB drive or copying malicious executables onto the device. This Action will only keep the subscribed event for as long as the PowerShell session is open.
Tags: ATT&CK:Lateral Movement, ATT&CK:Initial Access, ATT&CK:T1091

Action Name: Host CLI - Process Hollowing with PowerShell
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a defense evasion technique known as process hollowing or RunPE. To perform process hollowing, a process is started in a suspended state. The process then has its code unmapped from memory and the space is then allocated to another a malicious executable. The malicious program is then run from within the first process.

This example uses a PowerShell script called [Start-Hollow](https://github.com/FuzzySecurity/PowerShell-Suite/blob/master/Start-Hollow.ps1) created by FuzzySecurity. In this example, an instance of notepad.exe is created in a suspended state to allow for process hollowing. The script will then write a variant of MIMIKATZ (2.1.1), mimikatzMay2018.exe, to the allocated memory. When reviewing the running processes, only notepad can be seen. Note: If this Action is run as Admin or Non-admin, the instance of MIMIKATZ can be seen in the screenshots. 

NOTE - This Action uses the Incompatible feature.
Tags: Tool:MIMIKATZ, ATT&CK:T1055.012, ATT&CK:T1093, CWE:119, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation

Action Name: Host CLI - Office Application Startup with Excel
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a persistence technique that leverages Microsoft Office Templates and VBA macros. Microsoft Office offers the option to add macros to these document templates. If added, the macros execute regardless of whether macros are disabled.  This Action uses Excel and personal templates to execute this technique. For the macro to run, the template must exist under %APPDATA%\Microsoft\Excel\XLSTART\PERSONAL.xlsb. 

More additional information on this technique can be found on [Hexacorn's Blog](http://www.hexacorn.com/blog/2017/04/19/beyond-good-ol-run-key-part-62/).

>**Pre-Requisites:**
Actor must have Microsoft Excel installed

Action Name: Host CLI - Execution via Compiled HTML Files
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates both a defense evasion and execution technique that leverages Compiled HTML Files (CHM). As the name suggests, CHM files consist of HTML files, indexes, and other tools which provide users an online help format for Windows OS. These files can contain various code including Java, VBA, or like in this Action, ActiveX.  Adversaries can utilize these files to execute malicious code on a machine and bypass application whitelisting. This Action executes the file locally and spawns notepad.exe.

The code used to generate the CHM file was adopted from Oddvar Moe's [GenerateCHM_1.0.ps1](https://gist.githubusercontent.com/api0cradle/95ae3c7120f16255d94088bd8959f4b2/raw/fa25b85e85bbb64c5cf021adf92b125357086a6f/GenerateCHM_1.0.ps1) and Nikhil "SamratAshok" Mittal's [Out-CHM.ps1](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/samratashok/nishang/master/Client/Out-CHM.ps1) PowerShell scripts.

Action Name: Host CLI - File Permission Modification (takedown.exe)
Action Description: This Action demonstrates how adversaries can modify file permissions on a system as a defense evasion technique. This Action utilizes takedown, an internal Windows tool, which allows an Administrator to recover access to files that they once were denied access to. By using takeown, the Administrator can take ownership of the file. Adversaries can use this tool to their advantage to ensure that they have proper access to specific files on a system.

Action Name: Host CLI - File Permission Modification (icacls.exe)
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates how adversaries can modify file permissions as a defense evasion technique. Discretionary access control lists (DACL) are one of two types of lists that make up access control lists. DACL's responsibilities include identifying what users or groups can access files. If DACL's do not exist for a file or object, then full access is given for that object.

This Action uses icacls, an internal Windows tool, to modify the DACL's on a text file to allow for a specific user to have full access to the file. Adversaries can use this technique as a way to evade defenses and access files that they typically would not have proper permissions to.
Tags: ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, CWE:284, ATT&CK:T1222.001
Target Status:

Action Name: Host CLI - Execution via XSL Script Processing
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a defense evasion and execution technique that leverages Extensible Stylesheet Language (XSL) files. XSL files transform and present information within an XML file and support a variety of different scripting languages. Adversaries can take advantage of the fact that XSL supports different scripting languages and use XSL files to execute malicious scripts and executables on a device. This technique can assist in bypassing application whitelisting as well.

There are two methods for performing this technique. This Action uses WMIC to execute JScript within an XSL file that is stored locally on the machine, but this technique also works for files stored remotely. The XSL file was adopted from Casey Smith's version which is located [here](https://gist.githubusercontent.com/caseysmithrc/68924cabbeca1285d2941298a5b91c24/raw/8574e0c019b17d84028833220ed0b30cf9eea84b/minimalist.xsl).
Tags: ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:T1220

Action Name: Host CLI - Code Signing on Windows 10
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the digital signing and validation of a PowerShell script in Window 10. In this Action, an actor uses PowerShell to craft a new X.509 code signing certificate and signs a PowerShell script using that crafted certificate. The certificate is then added to the root certificate store on the system. Once the certificate is added to the store, the "Get-AuthenticodeSignature" cmdlet is executed to confirm if the signature is valid. This Action provides Mandiant Security Validation users with a means to evaluate how security endpoint tools and practitioners handle new digital signatures that are being used to sign files such as scripts and executables. The "New-SelfSignedCertificate" PowerShell cmdlet is required for this Action to run properly. If "New-SelfSignedCertificate" cmdlet is unavailable, the Action will produce an error result.

In certain Windows environments, the execution policy defines if a system can execute PowerShell scripts. For example, if the execution policy is set to "Restricted" (The default policy on Windows 10), PowerShell scripts cannot be executed. If the execution policy is set to "AllSigned", PowerShell scripts that are digitally signed can be executed on the system. A user can see their current execution policy by invoking the "Get-ExecutionPolicy" cmdlet in PowerShell and Administrators can change this policy with "Set-ExecutionPolicy".
Tags: ATT&CK:T1553.002, CAPEC:479, ATT&CK:T1553.004, ATT&CK:T1116, CWE:347, CWE:290, ATT&CK:T1130, CWE:295, CWE:327, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, CWE:284

Action Name: Host CLI - Disable Windows Update Service
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates how to disable the Windows Update service temporarily. The Windows Update service assists in managing updates and hot fixes on Windows operating systems. If this service is disabled, the machine cannot automatically detect when updates are available. Adversaries can take advantage of this service by disabling it in an attempt to stop any further updates on a compromised machine that could result in a loss of persistence.

Note - This Action will error if the Windows Update Service is already disabled.

Action Name: Host CLI - API Hooking Using Mavinject
Action Description: This Action demonstrates API hooking using mavinject. In this Action, a Dynamic Link Library (DLL) file is injected into an instance of PowerShell that invokes the "Invoke-WebRequest" cmdlet to access an SSL-enabled website. This injection causes the execution flow of the functions "EncryptMessage" and "DecryptMessage" to redirect to the abiritary code within the DLL file in a technique known as inline hooking. The code reveals the cleartext of the encrypted web traffic.

Action Name: Host CLI - Enable Remote Desktop with Netsh
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a malicious actor enabling Remote Desktop via netsh. Network shell, also known as netsh, is a command-line utility tool that allows users to configure and display network settings and roles. The command executed in this Action will enable Remote Desktop, which opens port 3389 for both TCP and UDP. This Action will first check to see if Remote Desktop is enabled. If it is, the Action will not run.

Action Name: Host CLI - DARKSIDE, Windows Share Creation
Action Description: This Action demonstrates the creation of a shared folder on a host via PowerShell. This tactic has been seen used by DARKSIDE threat actors to further spread DARKSIDE across the network. DARKSIDE is a ransomware written in C that may be configured to encrypt files on fixed and removable disks as well as network shares. DARKSIDE operates as a ransomware-as-a-service (RaaS) affiliate program and has been used in campaigns since at least August 2020. Like many other ransomware actors, the DARKSIDE affiliates conduct multifaceted extortion--they exfiltrate victim data, deploy DARKSIDE ransomware, and threaten to publish the stolen data to their blog--to pressure victims into paying the ransom.
Tags: Ransomware, ATT&CK:Execution, Malware:DARKSIDE, ATT&CK:Collection, ATT&CK:T1086, ATT&CK:T1059.001, ATT&CK:T1074

Action Name: Host CLI - In-Memory Download, Execution with WMI
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the use of WMI to download and execute a payload entirely in memory.  In this scenario, a XSL file is downloaded, and spawns notepad when executed.

This has been observed being used by [Astaroth](https://www.microsoft.com/security/blog/2019/07/08/dismantling-a-fileless-campaign-microsoft-defender-atp-next-gen-protection-exposes-astaroth-attack/).

For additional examples of malicious WMI activity, see the [LOLBAS project](https://lolbas-project.github.io/lolbas/Binaries/Wmic/).
Tags: ATT&CK:T1047, ATT&CK:T1220, ATT&CK:T1105, ATT&CK:Command and Control, ATT&CK:Execution, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion

Action Name: Host CLI - In-Memory Download, Execution with Rundll32, Javascript, Powershell
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the use of Rundll32, Javascript, and Powershell to download and execute a payload entirely in memory.  In this scenario, an encoded Powershell command is downloaded, and spawns notepad when executed.

For additional examples of Living off the Land attacks, see the [LOLBAS project](https://lolbas-project.github.io/).

Action Name: Host CLI - In-Memory Download, Execution with Regsvr
Action Description:

For additional examples of malicious Regsvr32 activity, see the [LOLBAS project](https://lolbas-project.github.io/lolbas/Binaries/Regsvr32/).

For additional examples of malicious Mshta activity, see the [LOLBAS project](https://lolbas-project.github.io/lolbas/Binaries/Mshta/).

Action Name: Host CLI - In-Memory Download, Execution with Msiexec
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the use of Msiexec to download and execute a payload entirely in memory.  In this scenario, Msiexec downloads an MSI and installs a non-existent program.  A JScript payload is included within the MSI, which will spawn notepad during the installation process.

For additional examples of malicious Msiexec activity, see the [LOLBas Project](https://lolbas-project.github.io/lolbas/Binaries/Msiexec/).
For more in-depth information about the specific malicious MSI activity that this action demonstrates, click [here](https://www.trendmicro.com/en_us/research/19/d/analysis-abuse-of-custom-actions-in-windows-installer-msi-to-run-malicious-javascript-vbscript-and-powershell-scripts.html).

Action Name: Host CLI - Execute Shellcode in Memory using PowerShell
Action Description: This Action demonstrates a host attempting to load and execute shellcode in memory using Powershell. This is a technique used by adversaries to evade defenses by loading a payload directly into memory. The Powershell code is obfuscated multiple times with Base64 and Gzip. The shellcode used opens notepad.

Action Name: Host CLI - Defense Evasion, Execution: Control Panel Items
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a malicious attacker using Control Panel Items to execute arbitrary code on a compromised machine.  The code is triggered by making a registry change and launching the control panel.  Notably, even Non-admin users are typically allowed to make changes to their own registry hive.  By indirectly executing the payload via the Control Panel, attackers attempt to bypass application whitelisting.

This particular technique has been observed in malware targeting banks in [Latin America](https://www.welivesecurity.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/CPL-Malware-in-Brasil-zx02m.pdf).

Please note that use of PowerShell from cmd is required to ensure proper cleanup.
Tags: ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, CWE:434, ATT&CK:T1218.002

Action Name: Host CLI - FIN13, Persistence Using Registry Keys
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the persistence mechanism FIN13 has used to persistently execute their backdoors. Registry run keys such as HKEYLOCALMACHINE\SOFTWARE\WOW6432Node\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run\hosts which was configured to execute a file located at C:\WINDOWS\hosts.exe. They have also created scheduled tasks with names such as acrotryr and AppServicesr to execute binaries of the same name in the C:\Windows directory.

In this action notepad.exe is copied to C:\Windows and renamed to hosts.exe to mimic malicious file name used by FIN13.
Tags: ATT&CK:Persistence, CWE:732, ATT&CK:T1547.001, CWE:15, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, FIN13

Action Name: Host CLI - FUSIONDRIVE, Create Mutex
Action Description:
This action demonstrates the creation of a mutex used by FUSIONDRIVE.  Additional information about FUSIONDRIVE can be found in [this report](https://advantage.mandiant.com/reports/21-00023856).

FUSIONDRIVE is a toehold backdoor written in C++ that leverages a OneDrive account for C&C. FUSIONDRIVE can enumerate and exfiltrate basic system information such as running processes and OS version. FUSIONDRIVE can also download and execute malicious code from a configured OneDrive account. Communications occur over TCP/443 HTTPS and uses the Microsoft Graph API to interact with the OneDrive resources.
Tags: ATT&CK:Execution, ATT&CK:T1559, Malware:FUSIONDRIVE, UNC3322

Action Name: Host CLI - Asynchronous Procedure Call
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates an Actor executing arbitrary code in the address space of a separate live process via asynchronous procedure call

Running code in the context of another process may allow access to the process's memory, system/network resources, and possibly elevated privileges. Execution via APC injection may also evade detection from security products since the execution is masked under a legitimate process.
Tags: ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:T1055.004, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion

Action Name: Host CLI - Dynamic-Link Library (DLL) Injection with Mavinject.exe
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates an Actor executing arbitrary code in the address space of a separate live process via DLL Injection.

Running code in the context of another process may allow access to the process's memory, system/network resources, and possibly elevated privileges. Adversaries may inject dynamic-link libraries (DLLs) into processes  in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate  privileges.
Tags: ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:T1055.001

Action Name: Host CLI - Modify Scheduled Task for Persistence
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates the use of schtasks to modify an existing scheduled task to gain persistence on an infected system. An actor can use existing tasks that run under the context of SYSTEM to maintain access with the highest privilege.

APT41 has used this technique, in the past and in the recent campaign, leveraging shell32.dll for binary execution.
Tags: ATT&CK:Persistence, ATT&CK:T1053.005, APT41, ATT&CK:Execution, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation

Action Name: Host CLI - Asynchronous Procedure Call using Early Bird Injection
Action Description: This Action demonstrates a host attempting to execute a benign custom-compiled C++ binary utilizing Asynchronous Procedure Call using the EarlyBird Injection technique. When executed, the binary creates a suspended calc.exe process and injects shellcode that drops a benign text file to disk once the process is resumed. Process injection is a method of executing arbitrary code in the address space of a separate live process, and may be used by adversaries to evade defense or escalate privileges.
Tags: ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:T1055.004, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion

Action Name: Host CLI - MSBuild Executing XML Document
Action Description: This Action demonstrates a host attempting to execute a malicious XML document with MSBuild. MSBuild is a .NET binary normally used for compilation of legitimate C# code but can be abused to compile and execute malicious code. Adversaries may take advantage of trusted developer utilities such as MSBuild to proxy execution of malicious payloads. There are many utilities used for software development related tasks that can be used to execute code in various forms to assist in development, debugging, and reverse engineering. These utilities may often be signed with legitimate certificates that allow them to execute on a system and proxy execution of malicious code through a trusted process that effectively bypasses application control solutions.
Tags: ATT&CK:T1127.001, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion

Action Name: Host CLI - Schtask Evasion, Delete Security Descriptor
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a host utilizing a persistence method used by TARRASK malware. TARRASK creates a scheduled task, and then deletes the SD (Security Descriptor) value in the registry. removal of this value results in the task "disappearing" from "schtasks /query" and Task Scheduler. The task is effectively hidden unless an examiner manually inspects the aforementioned registry paths.

More information about this technique can be found [here](https://www.microsoft.com/security/blog/2022/04/12/tarrask-malware-uses-scheduled-tasks-for-defense-evasion/).

NOTE - This Action uses the Incompatible feature.
Tags: ATT&CK:T1053.005, ATT&CK:T1112, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:Persistence, ATT&CK:Execution, CWE:15, CWE:732, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation

Action Name: Host CLI - Path Interception by Search Order Hijacking
Action Description: This Action demonstrates executing a program via path interception by search order hijacking. Action Name: Host CLI - Active Directory Reconnaissance with SHARPHOUND, Session Dump, PowerShell
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a malicious actor leveraging the tool SHARPHOUND to collect session information on Active Directory. This Action uses the "Session flag" which collects users' session information from across the domain. Note: This Action leverages the PowerShell variant of SHARPHOUND.

SHARPHOUND is the data ingestion utility used by newer versions of BLOODHOUND to collect information about an Active Directory environment. SHARPHOUND is written in C# and re-implements BLOODHOUND's older PowerShell-based data ingestion utility.

>**Pre-Requisites:**
Actor must be domain-joined to properly configured Active Directory environment

Action Name: Host CLI - Component Object Model Hijacking with the Local Server Switch
Action Description: This Action demonstrates Component Object Model (COM) hijacking by creating registry values under InprocServer32 key in the HKCU hive then calling the Class ID to be executed via "rundll32.exe -localserver [clsid]". This method is generally used as an alternative to 'rundll32.exe -sta [clsid]' to execute dll's while evading detection. Adversaries may establish persistence by executing malicious content triggered by hijacked references to COM objects. Adversaries can use the COM system to insert malicious code that can be executed in place of legitimate software through hijacking the COM references and relationships as a means for persistence.

Action Name: Host CLI - Control Panel Items, Without Reg.exe
Action Description: This Action demonstrates an Actor executing a malicious payload (A DLL with a shellcode loader) by leveraging Windows Control Panel items. Control Panel items can be loaded by using the Windows utility control.exe. While loading the Control Panel item referenced malicious binaries will be executed by control.exe. Since the process which loads the malicious code is a signed Windows binary this technique is commonly used as a method to bypass application whitelisting.  Upon successfull execution of this payload the victim creates a reverse tcp connection via port 80 to a fictious IP of 10.10.10.10.

Action Name: Host CLI - APT29, Creation of WMI Class with PowerShell
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates an actor creating a new WMI class via PowerShell. The Action creates a new class entitled RacTask under the namespace "root\cimv2" and assigns a string property named HiveUploadTask. The value of the property is a base64 encoded command that executes notepad.exe.

According to Mandiant Threat Intelligence, APT29 has leveraged WMI to obtain persistence by creating the same class name and properties as this Action. Instead of a base64 encoded PowerShell command to execute notepad.exe, the HiveUploadTask property contained encrypted and base64 encoded code for POSHSPY.  More information can be found on the Mandiant Threat Intelligence Portal: [17-00003208](https://advantage.mandiant.com/reports/17-00003208).

Action Name: Host CLI - APT29, Persistence through WMI Event Subscription
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates an actor compiling a MOF file on a host to create a new WMI event subscription. The MOF file, managed object format, is compiled using the command-line utility tool mofcomp.exe. 

Three main components are needed in the file to create the new event subscription: \_\_EventFilter, EventConsumer, \_\_FilterToConsumerBinding. Specifically in this file, the EventConsumer's job is to execute a base64 PowerShell encoded command every Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday at 11:33 a.m. local time, which is defined by the \_\_EventFilter. The PowerShell command in this Action simply executes notepad.exe.

According to Mandiant Threat Intelligence, APT29 has leveraged WMI Event Subscriptions to obtain persistence on a targeted machine. Specifically, APT29 used POSHSPY, which contained a WMI component to execute an additional PowerShell component of the backdoor. More information on this specific technique can be read about here: [17-00003208](https://advantage.mandiant.com/reports/17-00003208).
Tags: ATT&CK:Persistence, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:Execution, ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, CAPEC:267, ATT&CK:T1086, ATT&CK:T1059.001, CWE:697, CWE:20, ATT&CK:T1027, CWE:173, 17-00003208, CWE:74, APT29, ATT&CK:T1047, ATT&CK:T1546.003, ATT&CK:T1084

Action Name: Host CLI - LNK with Embedded PowerShell Commands, Notepad.exe
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a user executing a shortcut file masquerading as a PDF. The target path of the shortcut file points to powershell.exe and a base64 encoded command. The encoded command's purpose is to carve additional embedded PowerShell commands within the .LNK and ultimately execute those commands. This specific sample will spawn a new instance of notepad.exe once executed. 

According to FireEye, APT29 has used similar techniques in past spearphishing campaigns. More information on these techniques can be read about on the Mandiant Threat Intelligence Portal: [18-00019759](https://advantage.mandiant.com/reports/18-00019759). The script used to generate the .LNK file can be found [here](https://uperesia.com/booby-trapped-shortcut).

Note: If an instance of notepad.exe is already running on the Actor, the job will return an error.
Tags: ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:Persistence, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:Execution, CWE:706, CAPEC:267, CAPEC:132, CAPEC:177, CWE:74, ATT&CK:T1036, CWE:697, ATT&CK:T1059.001, ATT&CK:T1086, APT29, CWE:20, ATT&CK:T1027, 18-00019759, ATT&CK:T1023, CWE:59, ATT&CK:T1547.009, CWE:173

Action Name: Host CLI - LNK with Embedded Executable
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates a user executing a shortcut file masquerading as a PDF. The target path of the shortcut file points to powershell.exe and a base64 encoded command. The encoded command's purpose is to carve additional embedded PowerShell commands, including an embedded executable within the file, writing it to disk and execute it. Please note - the executable embedded in the file simply writes to a text file in the C:\Users\Public\Documents directory. 

According to FireEye, APT29 has used similar techniques in past spearphishing campaigns. More information on these techniques can be read about on the Mandiant Threat Intelligence Portal: [18-00019759](https://advantage.mandiant.com/reports/18-00019759). The script used to generate the LNK file can be found [here](https://uperesia.com/booby-trapped-shortcut).
Tags: ATT&CK:Privilege Escalation, ATT&CK:Persistence, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:Execution, CWE:706, CAPEC:267, CAPEC:132, CAPEC:177, CWE:74, ATT&CK:T1036, CWE:697, ATT&CK:T1059.001, ATT&CK:T1086, APT29, CWE:20, ATT&CK:T1027, 18-00019759, ATT&CK:T1023, CWE:59, ATT&CK:T1547.009, CWE:173

Action Name: Host CLI - APT29, Timestomping with PowerShell, POSHSPY
Action Description:
This Action demonstrates an actor timestomping a file through the use of PowerShell. Before changing the timestamps of the file, the Host CLI Steps check for a random file under C:\Windows\System32 that was last written to before 2013 and grab the file's properties. The Action will gather the Creation Time, Last Accessed Time, and Last Write Time from the randomly selected file and modify the same file properties for the dropped executable.

According to Mandiant Threat Intelligence, APT29 has leveraged POSHSPY, a backdoor that uses PowerShell and WMI to achieve persistence through living off the land, in past campaigns. POSHSPY has built-in functionality to perform the same timestomping commands used in the Action. More information about this technique can be read about on the Mandiant Threat Intelligence Portal: [17-00003208](https://advantage.mandiant.com/reports/17-00003208).
Tags: ATT&CK:T1099, Malware:POSHSPY, 17-00003208, APT29, ATT&CK:T1086, ATT&CK:Execution, ATT&CK:Defense Evasion, ATT&CK:T1070.006, ATT&CK:T1059.001

Action Name: Host CLI - Named Pipe Impersonation, Privilege Escalation
Action Description: This Action demonstrates the use of the named pipe impersonation technique. Named pipes is a Windows mechanism that enables two unrelated processes to exchange data between themselves, even if the processes are located on two different networks. It's very similar to client/server architecture. It is possible for the named pipe server to impersonate the named pipe client's security context by leveraging the ImpersonateNamedPipeClient API.

Action Name: Host CLI - Active Directory, Net Group, Domain Controllers
Action Description:

>**Pre-Requisites:**
